23 may provide the requisite notice to the parent or Indian custodian and
24 the tribe or tribes. Notice shall be provided within five days after the
25 initiation of voluntary services.
26 (3) When the department or the state offers the parent or Indian
27 custodian services through a voluntary foster care placement or in-home
28 services, the Indian custodian of the child and the Indian child's tribe
29 or tribes have a right to participate in, provide, or consult with the
30 department or the state regarding the provision of voluntary services.
31 (4) When the department or the state offers the parent or Indian
-33-

LB1032 LB1032
2026 2026
1 custodian services through a voluntary foster care placement or in-home
2 services, the department or the state shall provide remedial services and
3 rehabilitative programs designed to prevent the breakup of the Indian
4 family or unite the parent or Indian custodian with the Indian child
5 until these efforts have proved unsuccessful.
6 (5) Prior to any voluntary relinquishment or termination of parental
7 rights proceeding in which the department or the state is a party or was
8 providing assistance to a parent or Indian custodian, the department or
9 the state or its designee shall submit the following information, in
10 writing, to the court if it has not previously been provided:
11 (a) The jurisdictional authority of the court in the proceeding;
12 (b) The date of the Indian child's birth and the date of any
13 voluntary consent to relinquishment or termination;
14 (c) The age of the Indian child at the time voluntary consent was
15 given;
16 (d) The date the parent appeared in court and was informed by the
17 judge of the terms and consequences of any voluntary consent to
18 relinquishment or termination;
19 (e) The parent fully understood the explanation of such terms and
20 consequences in English or, when necessary, the explanation was
21 interpreted into a language that the parent understood and the parent
22 fully understood the explanation of such terms and consequences in the
23 language into which such terms and consequences were translated;
24 (f) The name and address of any prospective adoptive parent whose
25 identity is known to the consenting parent;
26 (g) The promises, if any, made to the parent, as a condition of the
27 parent's consent, including promises regarding the tribal affiliation or
28 health, ethnic, religious, economic, or other personal characteristics of
29 any adoptive family with which the child would be placed; and
30 (h) The details, if any, of an enforceable communication or contact
31 agreement authorized by section 43-162.
-34-

LB1032 LB1032
2026 2026
1 (6) In the case of an Indian child who may be eligible for a tribal
2 customary adoption, the court shall not order termination of parental
3 rights under this section unless and until the court determines that such
4 adoption would not be an appropriate permanency plan and would not be in
5 the best interests of the Indian child. It shall be sufficient
6 justification to find that a tribal customary adoption would not be an
7 appropriate permanency plan and would not be in the best interests of the
8 Indian child if:
9 (a) Notice was provided to the tribe of the Indian child as provided
10 in section 20 of this act; and
11 (b) By the time of the initial appearance of the parties on the
12 termination of parental rights, the tribe did not file an objection with
13 the court stating its belief that tribal customary adoption would be
14 appropriate for the child and in the best interests of the Indian child.
15 (7) (6) Any parent or Indian custodian may withdraw consent to a
16 foster care or voluntary foster care placement under state law at any
17 time and, upon such withdrawal, the child shall be returned to the parent
18 or Indian custodian.
19 (8) (7) In any voluntary proceedings for termination of parental
20 rights to, or adoptive placement of, an Indian child, the consent of the
21 parent may be withdrawn for any reason at any time prior to the entry of
22 a final decree of termination or adoption, as the case may be, and the
23 child shall be returned to the parent.
24 (9) (8) After the entry of a final decree of adoption of an Indian
25 child in any state court, the parent may withdraw consent thereto upon
26 the grounds that consent was obtained through fraud or duress and may
27 petition the court to vacate such decree. Upon a finding that such
28 consent was obtained through fraud or duress, the court shall vacate such
29 decree and return the child to the parent. No adoption which has been
30 effective for at least two years may be invalidated under the provisions
31 of this subsection unless otherwise permitted under state law.
-35-

LB1032 LB1032
2026 2026
1 Sec. 22. Section 43-1507, Reissue Revised Statutes of Nebraska, is
2 amended to read:
3 43-1507 Any Indian child who is the subject of any action for foster
4 care placement or termination of parental rights under state law, any
5 parent or Indian custodian from whose custody such child was removed, and
6 the Indian child's primary tribe may petition any court of competent
7 jurisdiction to invalidate such action upon a showing that such action
8 violated any provision of sections 43-1504 to 43-1506 or sections 20 and
9 23 to 29 of this act.
10 Sec. 23. (1) If a state court finds that tribal customary adoption
11 is an appropriate permanency plan under section 43-1312 and is in the
12 best interests of an Indian child and the Indian child's tribe consents
13 in writing to the tribal customary adoption, the state court shall grant
14 temporary concurrent jurisdiction to the tribal court of the Indian
15 child's tribe for the sole purpose of finalizing a tribal customary
16 adoption according to the custom, traditions, and laws of such tribe and
17 the best interests of the Indian child.
18 (2) Within thirty days after the granting of temporary concurrent
19 jurisdiction under subsection (1) of this section, the department shall:
20 (a) Provide written notice to the Indian child's tribe describing:
21 (i) The elements that an order or judgment for tribal customary
22 adoption must include to be accepted by the state court as described in
23 subdivision (2)(a) of section 26 of this act;
24 (ii) The documents, reports, or other information that must be filed
25 with the state court upon transfer back to the state court for accepting
26 the order or judgment for tribal customary adoption as described in
27 subdivision (2)(b) of section 26 of this act; and
28 (iii) The tribe's right to conduct, or designate another to conduct,
29 the adoptive home study as described in section 24 of this act;
30 (b) Provide the Indian child's tribe and proposed tribal customary
31 adoptive parents with a written report on the Indian child. Such report
-36-

LB1032 LB1032
2026 2026
1 shall include, to the extent not otherwise prohibited by state or federal
2 law:
3 (i) The medical background and tribal affiliations, if known, of the
4 child's biological parents; and
5 (ii) The child's educational information, developmental history, and
6 medical background, including all known diagnostic information, current
7 medical reports, and psychological evaluations; and
8 (c) Provide the Indian child's tribe a copy of all court filings,
9 including attachments and exhibits, from the state court proceeding, to
10 the extent not otherwise prohibited by state or federal law.
11 Sec. 24. (1) An Indian tribe participating in a tribal customary
12 adoption may conduct the adoptive home study required by section 43-107,
13 or designate another party to conduct such study in consultation with the
14 tribe, so long as the study meets the nationally accepted standards for
15 tribal licensing and approval.
16 (2) The state court shall accept such home study if the study uses
17 the prevailing social and cultural standards of the Indian child's tribe
18 as the standards to evaluate the proposed tribal customary adoptive
19 placement.
20 Sec. 25. The tribe of an Indian child who is subject to a pending
21 tribal customary adoption may work in consultation with the department as
22 the department works with the proposed tribal customary adoptive parents
23 to finalize the written adoption assistance agreement as described in
24 section 43-118.02 in order to ensure that the Indian child has access to
25 all available state, federal, and tribal resources for which such child
26 is or will be eligible after the decree of adoption, including, but not
27 limited to, services through the Indian Health Service.
28 Sec. 26. (1)(a) Within one hundred twenty days after receiving
29 notice of the transfer of concurrent jurisdiction under section 23 of
30 this act, the tribal court shall:
31 (i) Finalize the order or judgment of tribal customary adoption;
-37-

LB1032 LB1032
2026 2026
1 (ii) Transfer proceedings back to state court; and
2 (iii) Provide the state court with a copy of such final order or
3 judgment.
4 (b) If the requirements of subdivision (1)(a) of this section are
5 not met within the one-hundred-twenty-day deadline, the grant of
6 concurrent jurisdiction to the tribal court shall expire and the
7 proceedings shall transfer back to the state court, unless the state
8 court finds that the Indian child's tribe has demonstrated good cause for
9 an extension. Extensions under this subdivision may be granted in
10 increments of no more than sixty days.
11 (2) The state court shall accept such order or judgment and give it
12 full faith and credit so long as:
13 (a) The order or judgment:
14 (i) Includes a description of:
15 (A) Any rights retained by the Indian child's biological parents or
16 Indian custodian, including contact to be maintained, if any, and the
17 rights of inheritance of the child; and
18 (B) The Indian child's legal relationship with the tribe;
19 (ii) Does not include any child support obligation from the Indian
20 child's biological parents or Indian custodian; and
21 (iii) If applicable and appropriate, has the findings required to
22 ensure the Indian child is eligible to receive Title IV-E or Nebraska
23 adoption assistance payments; and
24 (b) Unless otherwise exempted, all documents and records required by
25 sections 43-102, 43-107, and 43-109 have been filed with the court, as
26 well as:
27 (i) A record of the Indian child and the biological parents' tribal
28 membership and affiliations; and
29 (ii) The most recently filed cumulative active efforts report as
30 described by subdivision (1)(h) of section 43-1503.
31 (3) If the state court accepts such order or judgment, the state
-38-

LB1032 LB1032
2026 2026
1 court shall enter a decree of adoption. Such decree shall include:
2 (a) A description of any rights retained by the Indian child's
3 biological parents or Indian custodian, including contact to be
4 maintained, if any, and rights of inheritance of the child, as specified
5 within the tribal customary adoption order or judgment;
6 (b) A statement that any parental rights or obligations not
7 specified in the tribal customary adoption order or judgment are
8 transferred to the tribal customary adoptive parents;
9 (c) A description of the Indian child's legal relationship with the
10 tribe; and
11 (d) If applicable and appropriate, the findings required to ensure
12 the Indian child is eligible to receive Title IV-E or Nebraska adoption
13 assistance payments.
14 (4)(a) Any parental rights or obligations not specifically retained
15 by the Indian child's biological parents in the decree of adoption are
16 conclusively presumed to transfer to the tribal customary adoptive
17 parents.
18 (b) The retention of any rights by the Indian child's biological
19 parents or Indian custodian, including contact to be maintained and
20 rights of inheritance of the child, as specified within the tribal
21 customary adoption order or judgment, shall not be grounds for
22 challenging or terminating the adoption on the basis that the biological
23 parent or Indian custodian retained any parental or custodial rights,
24 responsibilities, or benefits.
25 (5) A prospective tribal customary adoptive parent is not required
26 to file a petition for adoption under section 43-102.
27 (6) Consent by the Indian child or their biological parents is not
28 required to enter a decree of adoption under this section.
29 (7) After the decree of adoption is entered, the tribal customary
30 adoption is legally complete and the juvenile court shall terminate its
31 jurisdiction over the Indian child.
-39-

LB1032 LB1032
2026 2026
1 Sec. 27. Nothing in sections 23 to 26 of this act is intended to
2 prevent the transfer of proceedings to a tribal court when transfer is
3 otherwise permitted under applicable law.
4 Sec. 28. A tribal customary adoption shall be accorded full faith
5 and credit by the courts of this state and shall be treated in all
6 respects as any other adoption for all other purposes under Nebraska law,
7 except to the extent otherwise provided for in the Nebraska Indian Child
8 Welfare Act.
9 Sec. 29. (1) The department may adopt and promulgate rules and
10 regulations to carry out sections 20 and 23 to 28 of this act and the
11 changes to other sections made by this legislative bill.
12 (2) The Supreme Court may adopt rules and forms to assist in the
13 carrying out of sections 20 and 23 to 28 of this act and the changes to
14 other sections made by this legislative bill.
15 Sec. 30. Original sections 43-107, 43-110, 43-116, 43-117,
16 43-117.02, 43-292, 43-1312, 43-1312.01, 43-1314, 43-1501, 43-1503,
17 43-1505, 43-1506, and 43-1507, Reissue Revised Statutes of Nebraska, and
18 sections 43-102, 43-104, 43-108, 43-109, 43-146.01, 43-246.01, and
19 43-292.02, Revised Statutes Cumulative Supplement, 2024, are repealed.
